equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic early representation transitions to charged surface context, selecting glutamate
equation_narrative.story: Position 51 in ubiquitin begins with a strongly hydrophobic representation character through layer 12, with alanine and valine dominating the logit lens (A peaks at 21% at L12, V at 16% at L19). This reflects the model reading local sequence patterns rather than structural context. Between layers 18-23, the representation shifts toward polar/charged character as structural and co-evolutionary information accumulates. The decision phase (L24-33) sees glutamate emerge decisively: E rises from 0.59% at L23 to 88% at L33, driven by strong MLP support at L28-32 and attention-based prediction channels at L30-33. The model correctly identifies this as a charged surface position.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a complex representation that evolves from hydrophobic to charged character. Early layers (1-12) show strong hydrophobic signal in the logit lens, with alanine peaking at 21% (L12) and valine at 16% (L19), reflecting local sequence patterns being read. The model reads 3 structural contacts and 2 co-evolving positions during this phase. Mid-layers (13-23) see a dramatic shift: polar residues (S, T, N) dominate the logit lens through L23, with serine reaching 19% and asparagine 31%. Key attention heads like L32:H9 (2.52 proj, structural writer) and L22:H8 (2.11 proj) begin gathering context. By L23, the representation has transitioned from encoding local hydrophobic patterns to encoding a polar/charged surface environment, though E itself remains at only 0.59%.
perception_phase.context_character: By layer 23, the model has assembled a representation consistent with a charged or polar surface-exposed position, with moderate co-evolutionary coupling (2 positions) and limited structural contacts (3 residues). The representation has shifted from hydrophobic-leaning (early layers) to polar-charged character (mid-layers).
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 3 residues read via attention, primarily through L32:H9 (structural writer, 0.89 structural attention)
Co-evolutionary signal: 2 coupled positions, read via L30:H3 (coevol eraser, 0.189 coevol attention)
Local sequence: Strong local attention throughout (L28:H18 with 0.965 local attention, L30:H14 with 0.904 local attention)
Early features (L1-9): Generic position encoding features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F9:5728) with 40-48 projection
Mid-layer features (L18): Representation character features emerge (F18:2075 with 20.55 proj, F18:2986 with 16.72 proj)

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes between layers 27-33. Glutamate emerges at L27 (3.2% to 14.3% by L30) and surges to dominance at L31-33 (15.9% → 88%). Layer 30 shows the strongest pro-E push (+7.67 total delta, driven by attention with +8.56 delta). MLP neurons at L28-32 provide sustained support: N28:889 (0.787 E-proj), N31:2865 (0.901 E-proj), N32:2783 (0.723 E-proj). Final layer features F33:3227 (MLP, 97.01 proj) and F33:326 (attention, 89.44 proj) act as strong E-specific prediction channels. Aspartate remains the runner-up throughout (10.34% final), reflecting the shared negative charge character.
decision_phase.transition: The perception-to-decision transition occurs sharply at L23-25. At L23, the logit lens shows asparagine leading at 31% with E at only 0.59%, reflecting a polar representation character. By L24, E-specific features begin activating (F24:2079 with 20.45 proj), and MLP neurons start casting real votes (N24:1012 with 0.425 E-proj). The representation shifts from encoding 'polar surface position' to actively predicting 'glutamate specifically' as high-enrichment prediction channels come online.

candidates.narrative: Glutamate emerges as the clear winner in the decision phase, rising from 0.59% at L23 to 88% at L33. The decisive push occurs at L30-33, driven by strong MLP support (N30:819 with 0.694 E-proj, N31:2865 with 0.901 E-proj, N32:2783 with 0.723 E-proj) and attention-based prediction channels (L32:H9 with 2.52 proj, L32:H17 with 2.45 proj). Final layer features F33:3227 (MLP, 97.01 proj) and F33:326 (attention, 89.44 proj) provide overwhelming E-specific support. The model correctly identifies this as a negatively charged surface residue.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L27-30, dominant by L31, peaks at L33
key_evidence: N31:2865 (0.901 E-proj) — strongest single MLP vote for E
L32:H9 (2.52 proj, structural writer) — integrates structural context for E
L30 velocity: +7.67 total delta toward E, attention-driven (+8.56 attn delta)

candidates.narrative: Aspartate remains the consistent runner-up throughout the decision phase, reaching 10.34% final probability. Like glutamate, D is negatively charged, and the model's representation captures this shared chemistry. D peaks at L31 (11.0%) before E's final surge. MLP neurons show moderate D support (N21:4815 votes 0.395 for D, N30:4283 votes 0.419 for D), but E-specific features ultimately dominate. The D vs E competition reflects the model distinguishing between two similar acidic residues based on side-chain length and local context.
candidates.key_layers: Steady presence L24-33, peaks at L31
key_evidence: N30:4283 (0.671 E-proj, 0.419 D-proj) — votes for both acidic residues
Maintains 10-11% through L29-33 as E surges
Shares negative charge character with winner

candidates.narrative: Alanine dominates the early logit lens, peaking at 21.13% at L12, but this reflects the hydrophobic character of the representation during perception, not a model prediction. Early layers read local sequence patterns that correlate with small hydrophobic residues. As structural and co-evolutionary information accumulates (L13-23), the representation shifts away from hydrophobic character, and A drops to 3.32% by L23. In the decision phase, A continues declining to 0.26% as charged-residue prediction channels activate. The early A signal was an artifact of incomplete context assembly.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks L12, declines L13-23, eliminated by L33
key_evidence: 21.13% at L12 in logit lens — reflects hydrophobic representation character
L13 velocity: -2.15 total delta away from A as representation shifts
N13:522 erases A (-0.166 A-proj, votes 0.226 for A but net negative for answer)

candidates.narrative: Valine shows strong early presence in the logit lens, peaking at 16.47% at L19. Like alanine, this reflects the hydrophobic character of the early representation as the model reads local sequence context. V starts high (12.17% at L0) and maintains presence through mid-layers, but declines sharply in the decision phase as the model commits to charged residues. By L33, V is at 0.36%. The early V signal indicates the representation was initially consistent with hydrophobic residues before structural context revealed the charged surface environment.
candidates.key_layers: High L0-L19, peaks L19, declines L24-33
key_evidence: 16.47% at L19 — peak hydrophobic representation character
N19:4937 votes 0.465 for V (but also 0.305 for E)
L20-23: multiple MLP erasers push away from hydrophobic character

candidates.narrative: Glutamine shows an early spike to 19.75% at L7, reflecting polar representation character in early layers. As a polar uncharged residue, Q appears in the logit lens when the model is assembling a polar context but before the charged nature is fully resolved. Q declines through mid-layers (0.56% at L23) and briefly resurges in the decision phase (5.47% at L29) before final elimination (0.61% at L33). The Q signal represents an intermediate stage where the model has identified polar character but not yet committed to negative charge.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks L7, declines L8-23, brief resurgence L29
key_evidence: 19.75% at L7 — early polar representation character
N32:2158 votes 0.967 for Q (but 0.831 for E) — polar/charged ambiguity
Final elimination as E-specific channels dominate

turning_points.description: The representation undergoes a major character shift from hydrophobic to polar. Alanine peaks at 21.13% at L12, then drops sharply as MLP erasers activate (N13:522 with -0.166 answer proj, N13:3398 with -0.194). Layer 14 shows -3.89 total velocity away from the answer, driven by attention (-2.88 delta). By L18, polar residues (T, S, L) dominate the logit lens. This reflects the model transitioning from reading local sequence patterns to integrating structural and co-evolutionary context that reveals the charged surface environment.

The perception-to-decision boundary. At L23, the representation is polar-leaning (N at 30.9%, S at 18.9%, E at 0.59%), encoding the biochemical context. L23 MLP neurons provide strong support (N23:4999 with 0.766 E-proj, total +1.31 answer proj), and L24 features begin activating E-specific prediction channels (F24:2079 with 20.45 proj). The representation shifts from 'this is a polar surface position' to 'this should be glutamate.' L25 shows -4.04 velocity as the model refines between polar candidates.

The final commitment to glutamate. L30 delivers the strongest pro-E push (+7.67 total delta, +8.56 from attention), driven by heads L30:H3 and L30:H14. MLP neurons at L30-32 cast decisive votes (N30:819 with 0.694 E-proj, N31:2865 with 0.901 E-proj, N32:2783 with 0.723 E-proj). L32 shows brief hesitation (-7.34 delta), but L33 resolves with both attention and MLP converging (+5.52 delta, 'both' driver). Final features F33:3227 (97.01 proj) and F33:326 (89.44 proj) lock in the prediction at 88%.

deep_dives.label: Early hydrophobic signal (L1-L12)
deep_dives.caption: Early features encode position identity and local sequence context. High projections (40-48) reflect the model reading local patterns that correlate with hydrophobic residues. This is representation assembly, not prediction — the model is gathering information about what's nearby, not yet deciding what should be here.

deep_dives.label: Representation shift (L13-L18)
deep_dives.caption: MLP neurons drive the transition from hydrophobic to polar representation character. Watch erasers like N13:522 (-0.166 answer proj, votes for A/T/V) and N18:691 (-0.447, votes for T/I/D) push away from hydrophobic residues. Writers like N15:4553 (0.373 E-proj) begin supporting charged candidates. Total answer projection swings from -0.92 (L13) to +2.77 (L19).

deep_dives.label: Structural context reading (L22-L32)
deep_dives.caption: Key attention heads integrate structural and co-evolutionary information. L32:H9 (2.52 proj, structural writer with 0.89 structural attention) reads 3D contacts. L30:H3 (-2.30 proj, coevol eraser with 0.189 coevol attention) processes evolutionary coupling. L28:H18 (-2.96 proj, local eraser) refines local context. These heads gather the evidence that distinguishes E from other polar residues.

deep_dives.label: Decision MLP neurons (L28-L32)
deep_dives.caption: MLP neurons cast the decisive votes for glutamate. N28:889 (0.787 E-proj), N31:2865 (0.901 E-proj), and N32:2783 (0.723 E-proj) provide sustained E-specific support. Total answer projection: +4.83 (L28), -0.88 (L29), +1.29 (L30), -1.76 (L31), +5.44 (L32). The oscillation reflects the model weighing E against D and other charged candidates before committing.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels (L33)
deep_dives.caption: Layer 33 features are highly E-specific prediction channels. F33:3227 (MLP, 97.01 proj) and F33:326 (attention, 89.44 proj) show the strongest support. These features have high enrichment for glutamate and fire specifically when the model has assembled sufficient evidence for a negatively charged surface residue. They represent the final commitment mechanism.

deep_dives.label: L30 velocity event
deep_dives.caption: Layer 30 shows the strongest single push toward glutamate: +7.67 total delta, driven primarily by attention (+8.56 attn delta, -0.89 MLP delta). This is where the model decisively commits to E over other polar candidates. Attention heads integrate structural and co-evolutionary evidence, while MLP provides supporting votes.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts glutamate by assembling a charged surface context through layers 1-23, then activating E-specific prediction channels in layers 24-33. Early layers (1-12) show hydrophobic representation character from local sequence reading, but structural contacts (3 residues via L32:H9) and co-evolutionary coupling (2 positions via L30:H3) shift the representation to polar-charged by L23. The decision phase (L27-33) sees glutamate surge from 0.59% to 88%, driven by strong MLP support (N31:2865 with 0.901 E-proj) and attention-based integration (L30 +8.56 attn delta). The strongest evidence is the convergence of structural context, co-evolutionary constraints, and E-specific prediction channels (F33:3227 with 97.01 proj) in the final layers, correctly identifying this as a negatively charged surface position in ubiquitin.
